    <para id="id9147526">2/ Motivation for the DTFT</para>
    <para id="id9732804">The relation among the x(t), s(t), (t), and x[n] is shown below as is the relation among the X(f), S(f), and (f).</para>
    <figure id="id9054155">
      <media id="id1170207199529" alt=""><image src="../../media/graphics3-0b22.png" mime-type="image/png" height="178" width="520"/></media>
    </figure>
    <para id="id8080512">How should we represent the Fourier transform of x[n]?</para>
    <para id="id9366265">How are the Fourier transforms of (t) and of x[n] related?</para>
    <para id="id7612327">II. THE DISCRETE TIME FOURIER TRANSFORM (DTFT)</para>
    <para id="id9122595">1/ Notation for CT and DT transforms</para>
    <para id="element-596"><media id="id1170211128691" alt=""><image src="../../media/bang0.png" mime-type="image/png" height="178" width="520"/></media></para>
    <para id="id8974282">2/ Relation of Z transform and Fourier transform of a DT signal</para>
    <para id="id9878054">The Z transform pair is defined as </para>
