    <para id="id5211961">requires solution of N algebraic equations with N unknowns. The solution involves N multiplications and additions for each value of m, i.e., N2 operations to compute  from x[n]. The FFT algorithm is a method for solving these equations that reduces the number of computations from N2 to N log2N. This is a remarkable reduction in computation. For example, suppose N = 1024, then N2=1,048,576 and N log2N = 1024 × 10 = 10, 240 a saving in computations of a factor of 102.4.</para>
    <para id="id9744721">VI. CONCLUSIONS</para>
    <para id="id9481904">The DTFT characterizes the frequency content of a DT signal in a manner analogous to the way the CTFT characterizes the frequency content of CT signal. Expansion/compression of DT signals was interpreted as compression/ expansion of the DTFT.</para>
    <para id="id9809162">The frequency domain methods were extended to cover both CT and DT signals and both aperiodic and periodic signals.</para>
    <para id="id9809171">The DFT, for which an efficient computational algorithm exists (FFT algorithm), was defined as a method to relate samples of the time function to samples of the Fourier transform.</para>
